          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823809?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">佛罗里达州州长罗恩·德桑蒂斯</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：查理·尼伯格/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>进步人士希望<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>赢得共和党提名，这解释了为什么他们歪曲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯</a>的新冠记录。媒体知道佛罗里达州州长反对封锁是一个政治卖点，因此他们正在以特朗普的方式改写历史。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>民主党人永远不会原谅德桑蒂斯先生违反封锁共识并在 2020 年春季重新开放他的州。美国人可以记得——尽管可能宁愿忘记——特朗普政府如何一次又一次地延长“15 天以减缓病毒传播”。</p><p>德桑蒂斯和其他一些共和党州长，尤其是佐治亚州的布莱恩·坎普和南达科他州的克里斯蒂·诺姆，在五月初通过放松病毒限制打破了常规。民主党人谴责德桑蒂斯“任其发展”，但他分阶段重新开放该州，并考虑到医疗保健系统治疗病人的能力。</p><p> 5 月 4 日，餐馆和零售店获准以 25% 的容量开业。两周后，德桑蒂斯宣布，如果能够保证顾客的安全，包括迪士尼世界在内的主题公园最早可以在 6 月提交重新开放的计划。六月，德桑蒂斯逐渐放松了其他限制。</p><p>那年夏天，新冠疫情席卷了佛罗里达州和南部各州，这些州基本上躲过了春季的第一波疫情。但德桑蒂斯在检查了数据并咨询了斯坦福大学的杰伊·巴塔查亚（Jay Bhattacharya）等科学家后，拒绝关闭企业。相反，他专注于保护面临更高风险的老年人。</p><p> 75 岁以上的老年人死于新冠病毒的可能性是年轻人的数百倍。封锁对年轻人的伤害更大，他们比新冠病毒更有可能死于吸毒过量。公共卫生官员狭隘地关注病毒风险，忽视了封锁造成的社会、经济和心理损害。</p><p>其中最重要的是学校停课造成的学习损失，这种损失可能永远无法弥补。尽管遭到教师工会的反对，德桑蒂斯先生还是少数几个在 2020 年秋季重新开放学校进行面对面学习的州长之一。他的重新开放减轻了学习损失，并帮助父母重返工作岗位。</p><p>德桑蒂斯先生的集中保护战略在《大巴灵顿宣言》中得到了阐述，尽管该宣言得到了证实，但进步人士仍然对其进行谩骂。 2020 年，佛罗里达州的按年龄调整的新冠死亡率在全国排名第十，尽管金州长期处于封锁状态，但该州的死亡率仍比加利福尼亚州低近 20%。</p><p>进步人士现在攻击德桑蒂斯涉嫌在疫苗问题上模棱两可，从而含蓄地承认德桑蒂斯的集中保护策略取得了成功。谣言是，州长最初支持为老年人接种新冠疫苗，但后来拒绝强制注射。他也没有威逼年轻人去获得它们。</p><p>这忽略了许多年轻人已经具有天然免疫力，这比疫苗更具保护性。疫苗还会导致年轻男性心肌炎，但美国疾病控制与预防中心却迟迟没有承认这一点。到 2021 年夏季，人们也清楚地认识到，疫苗只能提供暂时的感染保护。</p><p>新闻报道将佛罗里达州在 2021 年夏季达美航空浪潮期间较高的死亡率归因于德桑蒂斯拒绝接受疫苗强制要求。但他们忽略了，佛罗里达州在去年冬天遭受的新冠疫情浪潮也比大多数州小得多。据我们所知，感染可以建立长达数月的人口层面的保护。</p><p> 2021 年末和 2022 年初，佛罗里达州的新冠死亡率低于大多数州。媒体喜欢精挑细选数据并重点关注离散时期，将德桑蒂斯描绘成死神。但佛罗里达州在大流行期间按年龄调整的总体新冠死亡率比美国平均水平低 13%，与加利福尼亚州大致相同。</p><p>佛罗里达州老年人的疫苗接种率为 94.4%，与大多数民主党执政的州相似。大约 79.6% 的 18 岁及以上佛罗里达州人接种了两剂疫苗，这一比例高于大多数州，包括密歇根州 (71.6%)、北卡罗来纳州 (77.1%) 和威斯康星州 (77.7%) 等民主党州长的州。</p><p>进步人士和特朗普也不会承认德桑蒂斯的抗疫策略被证明是经济的福音。 2020 年 4 月至 2022 年 7 月期间，有 622,476 人从其他州搬到佛罗里达州，其中包括希望孩子上学的家庭。自 2020 年 1 月以来，佛罗里达州的就业增长了 7.4%，而加利福尼亚州的就业增长了 2.5%，纽约则下降了 1.2%。</p><p>封锁造成的损害仍在继续，但进步人士不能承认他们错了。特朗普先生也不能。因此，他们正试图推翻德桑蒂斯先生的正确观点。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-covid-record-lockdowns-vaccines-donald-trump-florida-1a6dbda2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantis-covid-record-lockdowns-vaccines-donald-trump-florida-1a6dbda2<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>共和党</category><category>罗恩·德桑蒂斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ranked-Choice Voting Was a Bad Choice]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>弗吉尼亚州阿灵顿县暂停了一项让许多选民感到困惑的系统。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590100480251187138"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590100480251187138"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:44 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ranked-choice-was-a-bad-choice-arlington-virginia-county-board-99264639"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822299?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Sue Dorfman/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>糟糕的结果并不总是足以阻止糟糕的政治实验，因此弗吉尼亚县委员会注意到了排名选择投票的证据。这种新奇的选举制度在进步改革者中风靡一时，但不太受选民喜爱。尝试过一次后，阿灵顿县迅速逆转。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>县委员会本月决定在 11 月大选中恢复普通多数投票。 “这并不是永远的‘不’，”董事会副主席利比·加维（Libby Garvey）在会议上表示。但“我们还没有考虑到真正的后果。”该委员会去年 12 月采用了排名选择，其首次部署是今年 6 月该县的民主党初选。</p><p>令人反思的原因之一可能是令人尴尬的结果。有六人参加竞选，两名初选获胜者是苏珊·坎宁安 (Susan Cunningham) 和莫琳·科菲 (Maureen Coffey)。他们在第一轮排名选择中获得第一和第三名。但排名第二的娜塔莉·罗伊在五轮计票后被淘汰，因为不太受欢迎的候选人被淘汰，他们的支持者被重新洗牌为第二、第三或第四受欢迎的候选人。</p><p>排名选择的支持者将这种类型的结果辩护为共识选择，而许多选民在回报到来时摸不着头脑。阿灵顿初选增加了一个进一步的复杂性，称为比例排名选择。由于这些选举有两名或两名以上获胜者，因此已经通过胜利门槛的候选人也会重新分配多余的选票。</p><p>如果你感到困惑，那么你的同伴就很好。 “也许我并不完全理解，”加维女士在会上说。 “我确实想知道我的选票如何计算。”该县共和党选举诚信团队的负责人弗兰克·卢斯比补充说，这种复杂性可能会让公民有理由怀疑一场势均力敌的竞选结果。</p><p>董事会成员和其他与会者表示对排名选择缺乏熟悉，但并不是因为缺乏努力。该县在采用该系统之前开展了宣传活动，包括模拟选举和公开问答。阿灵顿是弗吉尼亚州第一个采用排名选择的县，它的改变当然应该让爱好者们停下来。最近，选举受到了足够多不必要的不​​信任，但这并没有使选举变得更加不透明和不直观。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:44:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ranked-choice-was-a-bad-choice-arlington-virginia-county-board-99264639</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ranked-choice-was-a-bad-choice-arlington-virginia-county-board-99264639<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>排名选择投票</category><category>弗吉尼亚州</category><category>木板</category><category>县</category><category>弗吉尼亚州</category><category>阿灵顿</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[UPS and the Art of the Teamsters Deal]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这家航运巨头通过加薪来避免罢工并获得灵活性。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110253490010726"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110253490010726"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ups-teamsters-deal-avert-strike-sean-obrien-3bb8e61e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823808?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，一名 UPS 司机在旧金山递送包裹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UPS" class="">联合包裹服务公司</a>为劳工和平付出了代价<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司正在提供一份慷慨的合同，以避免即将发生的罢工。这笔交易显示了工人在紧张的劳动力市场中的实力，但也可以帮助公司为未来定位。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>卡车司机工会周二宣布，已与 UPS 达成一项为期五年的劳工协议。该协议避免了 330,000 名 UPS 工人举行罢工，他们投票决定，如果不能达成协议，最早将于 8 月 1 日罢工。正式谈判于 7 月初陷入僵局，但中止的高风险使该公司得以继续谈判。</p><p>卡车司机本周同意的报价包括大幅、快速的工资上涨。工会表示，占 UPS 员工一半以上的兼职工人的工资将立即提高至最低每小时 21 美元。这比目前 15.50 美元的最低价格有了巨大的飞跃，UPS 此前曾提出到 2025 年将最低价格提高到 20 美元，五年内每年的涨幅约为 7%。终身司机的工资也将上涨，平均最高费率从现在的 42 美元每小时提高到 49 美元，或者说五年内每年上涨约 3.4%。</p><p>这些巨额加薪将帮助卡车司机协会主席肖恩·奥布莱恩(Sean O&#39;Brien)向普通员工推销这笔交易，而普通员工将在未来几周内批准该协议。奥布莱恩先生希望出于销售目的大幅增加收入，白宫也是如此，白宫希望吹嘘拜登经济学帮助工会工人。</p><p> UPS 愿意支付这个价格来避免罢工，安德森经济集团估计罢工将在短短 10 天内让该公司损失 8.16 亿美元。该组织还估计，由于 UPS 每天递送约 2500 万件包裹，一旦发生罢工，整个经济将损失 70 亿美元。</p><p> UPS 还愿意付费以实现其在工作安排和新技术方面具有更大灵活性的目标。该公司并没有吹嘘这一点，但我们被告知该协议将允许在周六和周日进行更多的仓库和交货班次，而目前这些班次人手不足。</p><p>工会面临的一个风险是大幅加薪，尤其是兼职员工的加薪，将激励 UPS 用机器人和技术取代工人。近年来，卡车司机工会的 UPS 会员人数随着公司的发展而不断壮大，但这份合同可能是工会 UPS 会员人数的最高纪录。</p><p> UPS 与 Teamsters 的交易增加了其他劳资谈判的风险，尤其是美国汽车工人联合会与美国三大汽车制造商的谈判。工资大幅上涨也将引起美联储的关注，美联储将工资上涨视为通胀威胁。我们认为 UPS 的工资上涨与近期通货膨胀的影响相比，其推动的价格上涨幅度更大。但美联储经济学家认为这是工资-物价螺旋式上升。</p><p>这笔交易的好处将在数年内对双方产生影响，但最好的消息是，这对购物者和企业来说是一种解脱。当工人需求量很大时，合同僵局很常见，但当罢工得以避免时，公众就会受益。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ups-teamsters-deal-avert-strike-sean-obrien-3bb8e61e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ups-teamsters-deal-avert-strike-sean-obrien-3bb8e61e<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>快递/信使</category><category>货运/物流</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>劳动争议</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> UPS</category><category>卡车司机</category><category>联合包裹服务</category><category>肖恩·奥布莱恩</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>劳资纠纷</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>快递员</category><category>使者</category><category>货运</category><category>后勤</category><category>运输</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Medical School Treatment for DEI]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>国家认证机构在定义多样性方面表现出灵活性。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590015643377555852"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590015643377555852"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:40 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-medical-school-treatment-for-dei-diversity-requirement-education-students-university-college-d5693c88"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823843?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些州一直在努力消除大学校园中的多样性、公平性和包容性（DEI）官僚主义，这对大学有利。但医学院对此表示抵制，声称改变可能会让他们面临国家认证机构的风险。这可能正在改变。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>医学教育联络委员会 (LCME) 对美国医学院进行认证。其章程规定，每所医学院都必须制定多元化政策，并为学生、教职员工“开展持续、系统、有重点的招聘和保留活动，以实现适合使命的多元化成果”。</p><p>但 LCME 现在表明其多样性要求并不像学校想象的那么僵化。在一封回复众议院教育和劳动力委员会调查问卷的信中，LCME 表示，文本中“没有任何内容”“规定医学院必须使用哪些类别的多样性来满足这一要素”。</p><p>认证标准并不“建立或定义医学院需要达到的任何定量结果”。 LCME 继续表示，每个医疗项目“都有权自行定义其选择优先考虑的多样性项目。”学校可以信赖认证机构在其自身的“使命、环境和地理区域”背景下使用“灵活性”。</p><p>这为密苏里州、田纳西州、犹他州和其他州寻求将 DEI 官僚机构从医学院中剔除的机会。密苏里州立法机关考虑了一项禁止学校“进行 DEI 审计”或雇用 DEI 顾问的法案，但后来因担心学校无法遵守州法律和国家认证机构的规则而放弃。</p><p>众议院教育委员会教育委员会和劳动力主席弗吉尼亚·福克斯 (Virginia Foxx) 在信中也公开了 LCME 关于 DEI 与禁止种族歧视法律之间关系的信息。当被问及是否会“要求或鼓励”医学院“区别对待申请人”或根据种族授予奖学金时，认证机构对这两个问题都回答“不”。</p><p>近年来，政治化的多样性在医学院中日益凸显，许多学校都调整了招生要求来解决这些问题。这引起了人们对下一代医生的优点和能力的担忧。</p><p>据反对政治化医学的专业人士组织 Do No Harm 称，至少 40 所医学院不再要求某些学生入学时参加 MCAT。但长期以来，这项测试一直被认为是衡量学生准备情况和成绩的最佳标准。哈佛大学最近退出了《美国新闻与世界报道》医学院排名，并指出参与会激励“制定政策来提高排名，而不是制定更高尚的目标”。</p><p>正如我们在北卡罗来纳州和佛罗里达州所看到的那样，无论是否有书面的多样性标准，认证机构在追求进步的政治议程时都可能反复无常。但医学院可以将认证机构最近的答复作为一个信号，减少以牺牲一流医学教育为代价来保护 DEI 的担忧。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-medical-school-treatment-for-dei-diversity-requirement-education-students-university-college-d5693c88</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-medical-school-treatment-for-dei-diversity-requirement-education-students-university-college-d5693c88<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>德伊</category><category>大学</category><category>医学院</category><category>学生</category><category>大学</category><category>教育</category><category>多样性要求</category><category>认可者</category><category>多样性</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>工作场所多元化</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Only Biden Can Elect Trump in 2024]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>亨特破坏了他父亲起诉竞争对手的连任策略。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590110051476362476"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590110051476362476"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">小</span><span class="author" itemprop="name">霍尔曼·W·詹金斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:26 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/only-biden-can-elect-trump-hunter-joe-irs-justice-2024-investigation-2f02c2cb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823583?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乔·拜登和亨特·拜登于 2022 年 8 月 13 日离开南卡罗来纳州约翰斯岛的圣灵天主教堂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Manuel Balce Ceneta/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>通常，司法部会任命一名特别检察官来解决公众对政府客观调查涉及自身事务的能力的怀疑。显然需要任命杰克·史密斯的“利益冲突”是不同的。拜登政府肯定希望<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>受到调查并被指控犯有尽可能多的罪行。它还想假装拜登政府不是这么做的。</p><p> 2016 年 6 月，我开始<a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-u-redefines-the-brand-1465338721" target="_blank" class="icon none">怀疑</a>希拉里·克林顿 (Hillary Clinton) 竞选策略的必然胜利：“哈哈哈，你只能跟着我，因为特朗普太糟糕了。”又来了。</p><p>拜登说得再清楚不过了，为了全国每一位民主党官员的利益，他宣称他希望特朗普成为他 2024 年的对手。不过，风险在于，堆积如山的刑事指控导致共和党人团结在特朗普周围，尽管这可能会在大选中玷污他，但这种过度杀伤最终可能会让公众感到不安。这可能开始看起来象征着拜登先生自己的需要。</p><p>毕竟他的需求很大。在特朗普先生身上，他找到了一位他可以不辩论、甚至尽量减少积极竞选活动的候选人，他表示，尊崇这样一位挑战者是不体面的。到明年，这样一个向选民隐瞒拜登日益虚弱的借口可能是他获胜的唯一希望。</p><p>独裁者和哈莱姆篮球队有一个共同的做法。他们试图安排他们知道自己最擅长的可怜对手。希拉里·克林顿(Hillary Clinton)可能因输给特朗普而受到批评。如果拜登先生帮助选择特朗普先生作为他的对手，然后无论如何都输给了他，那么他正在努力成为一个完全不同的民主党反英雄。</p><p>因为，正如一些选民会理解的那样，用来打击特朗普的法律并不是一个客观的机制。纽约市与斯托米·丹尼尔斯有关的案件被普遍认为是有影响力的。 1 月 6 日的指控将是有效的，因为不负责任地声称选举被盗并不是犯罪，而且民主党人已经多次沉迷于这种行为。尽管特朗普先生在处理官方文件时为自己创造了各种责任，但如果拜登先生希望将其作为民事问题来处理，那么它就会作为民事问题来处理。</p><p>但亨特·拜登打破了所有这一切作为法律客观展开的光环。公众面临着两名国税局举报人和一名前联邦调查局监管特工的有说服力的证词，拜登司法部故意拖延，以免年轻的拜登先生因涉嫌在其父亲担任副总统期间涉嫌乌克兰问题而受到严重指控。总统。</p><p>亨特是拜登竞选期间出现的一个潜在黑洞。他已经 53 岁了，但除了出席每次白宫活动和总统出访之外，没有什么更好的事情可做。为什么？因为拜登先生对儿子的陪伴不够？或者是因为加强亨特的第一家庭特权地位是竞选活动的万福玛丽希望确保他获得司法部和媒体授予的豁免权至少持续到选举日？</p><p>华盛顿供应商 Axios 最近揭露了乔·拜登的所谓公开秘密</p>盛怒之下，咒骂下属。有些人甚至害怕与他单独相处。然而，在大量泄露的私人信息中，这种特质似乎从来都不是针对他的儿子的。在公开场合，拜登对亨特与他兄弟的遗孀短暂的恋情、他与亲子关系的斗争、他对税收和枪支指控的认罪感到满意。是否还有媒体辩护者仍然假装这充满了真实的父母爱和宽容的味道？<p></p><p>在白宫发现一袋可卡因。没有人想知道它是如何到达那里的。所有人都很乐意改变话题，奇怪的是，这突显了一种隐含的孝顺勒索的情绪，这种情绪如今似乎定义了父子关系。</p><p>在大量的证据中，假装乔没有默许他的儿子从外国影响力寻求者那里鲁莽地追求数百万美元的行为已经不再合理。拜登先生要承担后果——包括在导致乌克兰战争的事件年表中，美国情报机构故意利用有关<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>(Vladimir Putin)俄罗斯的虚假指控作为烟幕弹，以保护拜登竞选团队免受纯粹个人笔记本电脑的影响。揭露他吸毒的儿子。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多商业世界</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-strikes-big-risk-is-a-nanny-without-a-plan-union-film-streaming-bde3c89f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">好莱坞罢工的最大风险是没有计划的“保姆”</a><span class="date">七月 21, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-evs-and-heat-waves-range-anxiety-tesla-emissions-climate-7baa0f7d?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">电动汽车和热浪</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 18 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-musk-zuckerberg-cage-match-twitter-threads-free-speech-ad-revenue-social-media-profit-e05ba039?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">马斯克与扎克伯格的笼式比赛已于</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 14 日</span>开始</li></ul></div></div><p>特朗普仍有望保证拜登明年连任，尽管越来越容易想象拜登是一些伤心的美国人觉得有必要为特朗普拉动杠杆的原因。</p><p>在没有通配符的情况下，美国将有两位主要政党的候选人，他们的竞选部分是出于个人动机，以控制司法部，并<em>在极端情况下</em>控制赦免笔。</p><p>我们可以加入主流媒体的行列，在很多事情上对自己撒谎，但这不是成年人选择的生活方式。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/only-biden-can-elect-trump-hunter-joe-irs-justice-2024-investigation-2f02c2cb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/only-biden-can-elect-trump-hunter-joe-irs-justice-2024-investigation-2f02c2cb<category> 2024 年选举</category><category>拜登家族</category><category>税务欺诈</category><category>国税局</category><category>举报人</category><category>检控</category><category>司法部</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Phony Korean ‘Peace’ Movement]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>其领导人克里斯蒂娜·安希望美军撤出半岛和太平洋地区，甚至夏威夷。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108220346304164"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108220346304164"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">池成浩</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:25 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-phony-korean-peace-movement-women-cross-dmz-human-rights-ahn-73d74222"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823309?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">分隔朝鲜和韩国的非军事区，2022 年 7 月 19 日。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：KIM HONG-JI/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>汉城</em></p><p>一个自封的和平团体联盟正计划本周在华盛顿举行“全国动员结束朝鲜战争”——与美国众议院和参议院的同行举行会议、集会和游说会议。一些立法者已经加入其中：众议员布拉德·谢尔曼 (Brad Sherman) 的《朝鲜半岛和平法案》已经吸引了 33 名共同提案国。</p><p>这种努力是一种欺骗。动员和立法都推动了朝鲜要求美国签署无条件和平协议的要求。亲平壤团体正在重复该政权的“敌对政策”，即朝鲜半岛的紧张局势是美韩军事演习、美军在韩国的存在以及美国的经济制裁造成的。</p><p>这个问题对我来说是个人的。我1982年出生在朝鲜。1996年我和我的家人都快要饿死了。为了生存，我不得不从货运列车上捡拾一些煤炭，然后在黑市上出售这些煤炭来购买食物。当我在铁轨上饿晕过去时，一列火车从我身上碾过，几乎完全切断了我的左腿和手臂，必须在没有麻醉或抗生素的情况下截肢。</p><p> 2006年，我拄着拐杖逃亡，穿越中国和东南亚数千英里，才到达韩国。我叛逃并于 2020 年当选为国民议会议员。</p><p>当我走向自由的时候，我无法想象在韩国和美国还有支持朝鲜政权的人和组织。他们的长期目标是美军从韩国撤军。这可能会导致朝鲜按照<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>的条件实现统一。</p><p>本周动员的主要组织者之一、Women Cross DMZ 的 Christine Ahn（其<a href="https://www.womencrossdmz.org/about-us/our-team/" target="_blank" class="icon none">顾问委员会成员</a>包括阿比盖尔·迪士尼 (Abigail Disney)、格洛丽亚·斯泰纳姆 (Gloria Steinem) 和爱丽丝·沃克 (Alice Walker) 等名人）<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8Z69IF68m84" target="_blank" class="icon none">表示</a>，她正在“努力将韩国从美国的枷锁中解放出来”帝国主义”，而美国是“世界的侵略者和帝国”。她还<a href="https://fluxhawaii.com/stop-anti-asian-hate-and-us-imperialism/" target="_blank" class="icon none">敦促</a>美国从亚太地区撤走所有军事基地和部队，甚至包括她称之为“被占领领土”的夏威夷。</p><p>安女士反对美国和韩国的朝鲜相关人权立法。妇女穿越非军事区的政策声明似乎将世界上所有的问题归咎于美国的“帝国主义”和以色列的“ <a href="https://www.womencrossdmz.org/a-feminist-peace-initiative-statement-on-peace-and-justice-for-palestine/" target="_blank" class="icon none">种族隔离</a>”。其声明谴责对朝鲜、伊朗、委内瑞拉和津巴布韦<a href="https://www.womencrossdmz.org/statement-for-a-feminist-foreign-policy-to-confront-the-coronavirus-pandemic/" target="_blank" class="icon none">的制裁</a>。</p><p>作为一个逃离了朝鲜这个反乌托邦噩梦国家、现在有幸生活在自由之中的人，我有义务警告我的美国朋友。得益于与美国的联盟以及绝大多数韩国人支持的稳定驻军，韩国已经安全地生活了70年。美国不应给予亲平壤极端分子合法性，因为他们认为美国是邪恶力量。</p><p><em>季先生是大韩民国国会议员。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-phony-korean-peace-movement-women-cross-dmz- human-rights-ahn-73d74222</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-phony-korean-peace-movement-women-cross-dmz- human-rights-ahn-73d74222<category>北朝鲜</category><category>韩国</category><category>战争</category><category>帝国主义</category><category>人权</category><category>夏威夷</category><category>华盛顿</category><category>行进</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Doom Guy’ Review: First-Person Perspective]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>回顾过去，快速奔跑和射击想象中的怪物是你在网上能获得的最纯真的乐趣。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590101722256376194"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823726?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">约翰·罗梅罗.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：娜塔莉·格里尔</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12136984570395233300204590101722256376194"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">史蒂文·普尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 25 日下午 6:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/doom-guy-review-first-person-perspective-94ae0e65"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>最初的第一人称射击游戏——一款从持枪玩家角度呈现动作的视频游戏——被称为“迷宫战争”，这是一个由三名高中生在 1973 年 NASA 考察旅行期间制作的绿色线框演示。直到 1992 年《德军总部 3D》发行后，这一类型才成为商业主宰，这是一款纳粹主题的泼彩游戏，在德国被禁止。一年后，以火星恶魔为主题的泼溅音乐节《毁灭战士》（在火星上并未被禁止）及其后续作品《雷神之锤》于 1996 年问世。《德军总部》、《毁灭战士》和《雷神之锤》均由传奇人物制作。 id Software 的开发人员，并帮助为后来的许多游戏设定了模板，包括《堡垒之夜》、《绝地求生》和总收入 300 亿美元的《使命召唤》系列。</p><p>约翰·罗梅罗 (John Romero) 是 id Software 的联合创始人之一，也是 20 世纪 90 年代影响深远的射击游戏的共同设计师。凭借其开创性的射手，罗梅罗先生成为视频游戏行业的第一位摇滚明星。他和id的战友们肆无忌惮地买了房子和法拉利。罗梅罗先生离开 id 创办另一家视频游戏公司后，他允许公关团队发布一则现已臭名昭著的广告，宣布“约翰·罗梅罗即将让你成为他的婊子”，以此来调侃他的下一款游戏。这则广告引起了广泛的强烈反对，但他至今仍未平息。在罗梅罗先生极具娱乐性和深思熟虑的回忆录《末日盖伊：第一人称生活》中，这位明星开发商回顾了这一事件以及他职业生涯中的其他事件，并表明他至少可以对此一笑置之。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/fe64eb72-97d2-403f-98a8-1f816957ad7a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>但我们有点超前了。 《末日盖伊》的长长前奏以轻松幽默的方式动人地描述了罗梅罗先生在亚利桑那州图森市的贫困童年。他的母亲后来告诉采访者，年轻的约翰是一个好孩子，“从未向母亲开枪” ;但他也和一个暴力且酗酒的父亲住在一起（尽管他很崇拜他），随后还有一个暴力的继父。孩子通过恐怖电影、《龙与地下城》角色扮演游戏和投币街机游戏找到了逃避的途径。 11 岁时，他在当地一所大学设立了一个计算机帐户，并开始对机器进行编程，使其执行他想要的操作，并将游戏保存在纸质打孔卡上。 （那是在 1979 年，正值计算机编程的早期阶段，年长的大学生非常乐意帮助一位热心的同伴，无论他多么年轻。）后来，罗梅罗先生将自己发明的游戏卖给了计算机杂志，并最终成立了自己的公司。</p><p>这是一个典型的美国白手起家的故事，但罗梅罗先生太讽刺了，无法用粗俗的胜利语气来呈现它。他仍然希望自己在成功之路上能够更好地处理一些事情，尤其是他与另一个人的合作，这成为了电子游戏历史上最有名的创意心理剧之一。那是约翰·卡马克（John Carmack），另一位程序员大咖，也是 id 联合创始人。一拍即合，两人很快就形成了一种模式：卡马克先生负责对游戏引擎进行编程，即让游戏机制以前所未有的快速和优美方式运行的低级代码，而罗梅罗先生则负责设计游戏体验。与第三位联合创始人汤姆霍尔。但罗梅罗先生和卡马克先生的性格截然相反。后者是那种在沮丧时会在早上把成绩单放在同事办公桌上的人，什么也不说。 （他给罗梅罗打了 C，他自己给了 A-。）最终，他们的关系恶化到无法修复的地步，并导致罗梅罗先生离开了公司。罗梅罗先生在他自己的悲痛而安抚的叙述中，将自己描绘成合伙企业中充满激情的人，而卡马克先生则是合乎逻辑的人。他们是连队的骨头和斯波克，没有柯克上尉在他们之间进行调解。</p><p>作者在讲述他的下一款视频游戏《离子风暴》的公开失败时，表现出了某种自我撕裂的喜悦（他警告说，“大部分都在走下坡路”），但他在向读者介绍最新情况时，仍然保持着坚定的乐观态度。他随后在移动和教育游戏领域的冒险，甚至暗示了新的第一人称射击游戏的到来。在书的结尾处，他提出了一个谦虚的教义问答：“优雅地失败。 。 。 。接受你的缺陷，重新加载你的保存，然后再试一次。”如果塞缪尔·贝克特是一名游戏玩家，他可能也会这么说。</p><p> Mr. Romero does not pretend that his life story encodes many golden nuggets of business wisdom or tips for creative fulfillment, aside from general heuristics such as that avoiding problems is bad, or that employees who spend their days throwing empty soda cans over cubicle partitions should probably be fired. His story is much more textured, shaded and amusing than that. Remarkably so, one is tempted to say, for a book by a programmer—but then Mr. Romero has self-deprecating fun with that stereotype, too. Recounting his early difficulty with striking the right tone between cocky and confident, he writes: “My wife, Brenda, calls this &#39;Programmer Nuance Deficit Disorder.&#39; By that, she means programmers don&#39;t generally deal in ambiguity.” The book is both a fascinating history of computers and videogames in the 1980s and &#39;90s, from “Pac-Man” to “Half-Life,” and a meditation on family, roots and forgiveness.</p><p> That&#39;s not to say the reader ever loses sight of Mr. Romero&#39;s silly joy at enabling players to aim a large weapon at enemies such as Adolf Hitler in an armored suit, a character its developers dubbed Mecha-Hitler. By the end, the author seems rightfully secure in the knowledge that his work has given simple demon-slaying pleasure to millions. The Manichaean horror-sci-fi scenarios of “Doom,” in which, as Mr. Romero explained at the time, “good is a space marine with guns,” might arguably have helped inspire Donald Trump&#39;s inauguration of the US Space Force, but the game was, after all, born in a less anxious age, when running fast and shooting imaginary monsters was the most innocent fun you could have online. Maybe it still is.</p><p> <em>Mr. Poole is the author of “Trigger Happy: Videogames and the Entertainment Revolution.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/doom-guy-review-first-person-perspective-94ae0e65</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/doom-guy-review-first-person-perspective-94ae0e65<category> Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>Toys/Games</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category>计算</category><category>Games Software</category><category> Leisure/Travel Goods</category><category>技术</category><category>Books</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> books</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category> arts</category><category> entertainment</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews</category><category> opinion</category><category> computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>toys</category><category> games</category><category>消费品</category><category>计算</category><category>games software</category><category>闲暇</category><category>travel goods</category><category> technology </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Affirmative Action in Contracting Faces Legal Peril]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> San Francisco lawmakers declared themselves guilty of discrimination so they could discriminate more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098162051579570"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098162051579570"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Judge Glock</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 6:23 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-in-contracting-faces-legal-peril-balancing-economy-ag-sba-73911fdb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821169?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Supreme Court in Washington, July 13.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mariam Zuhaib/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In <em>Students for Fair Admissions v. Harvard</em> , the Supreme Court held that “racial balancing” was “patently unconstitutional,” and that affirmative action has to have a “logical end point.” There&#39;s been a lot of commentary about how that will apply to employment law but less about another program of racial discrimination: favoritism to racial minorities in government contracts.</p><p> Yet <em>Fair Admissions</em> is already affecting this area of law. Last week Judge Clifton Corker struck down minority contracting preferences at the Small Business Administration and US Department of Agriculture on grounds that existing requirements have little justification and “no logical end point.”</p><p> Minority contracting requirements have had deleterious effects on almost every aspect of government for decades. They have cost taxpayers countless billions, degraded government services, and deepened racial divisions. Almost a tenth of the American economy goes through government contracts, which involve everything from building submarines to installing software. Federal, state and local governments have set goals for percentages of these contracts that should be awarded to minority-owned businesses. To hit the goals, government officials can “set aside” contracts for minority firms, offer no-bid deals to minority contractors, or select minority contractors with higher bids than competitors.</p><p> Because of current racial obsessions, the scale of such favoritism is increasing. The federal government has awarded about 10% of its available contracts to minorities, but President Biden announced that he wanted to increase that to 15% by 2025. New York City and state have set goals of 30% of contracts going to businesses owned by minorities or women. Mayor Eric Adams has demanded more no-bid contracts.</p><p> The price of these programs is substantial. A 2009 <a href="https://direct.mit.edu/rest/article-abstract/91/3/503/57781/How-Costly-Is-Affirmative-Action-Government?redirectedFrom=fulltext" target="_blank" class="icon none">study</a> looked at highway costs after California voters banned consideration of race in government programs in the 1990s. It found that costs fell 5.6% relative to federally funded projects, in which racial contracting goals still applied. Other research <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4168912" target="_blank" class="icon none">shows</a> these requirements increase cost overruns and delays.</p><p> Minority contracts also encourage fraud. White contractors often use minority “front companies” to win contracts, then pay a small fee to the purported owner. Minority contractors often use bribes to keep getting special government solicitude. There is a steady drumbeat of indictments based on these programs.</p><p> In <em>Richmond v. Croson</em> (1989) and <em>Adarand Constructors v. Pena</em> (1995), the Supreme Court said that government could use minority contracting programs only under rare circumstances and to remedy past discrimination. Instead of adhering to these rulings, governments have fostered an industry of “disparity studies” firms. Governments pay these contractors—themselves often minority-owned—hundreds of thousands of dollars to tell them they&#39;ve been discriminating against minorities in contracting.</p><p> Governments then use disparity studies&#39; findings to show courts why they must discriminate in novel ways. As the California Supreme Court <a href="https://casetext.com/case/coral-const-v-city-and-county-of-san-francisco#p335" target="_blank" class="icon none">noted</a> in a 2010 ruling, the City of San Francisco issued legislative findings that it was still “actively discriminating against women and minority groups in its contracting.” Rather than simply stop discriminating, the city claimed it was justified in discriminating in favor of women and minority groups.</p><p> In <em>Fair Admissions,</em> Chief Justice John Roberts</p> cited <em>Croson</em> and <em>Adarand</em> six times to highlight the problems with all forms of racial discrimination. Today&#39;s minority-contracting programs should fall under the standards the court set forth. As Judge Corker observes, <em>Fair Admissions</em> “concerned college admissions programs, but its reasoning is not limited to just those programs.”<p></p><p> Today, minority contracting engages in explicit racial balancing. New York City&#39;s code demands that Hispanics get 8.99% of professional-services contracts and Native Americans get 0.65%. It is difficult to claim these programs are necessary to remedy past discrimination when they have been going on for decades. They still have no “logical end point.”</p><p> Minority contracting was always an inappropriate way to remedy America&#39;s history of racial injustice. It has favored a few connected businesses, encouraged fraud, burdened taxpayers with poor and expensive services, and further divided Americans. The justices should, and surely will, take another look.</p><p> <em>Mr. Glock is director of research at the Manhattan Institute and author of “The Dead Pledge: The Origins of the Mortgage Market and Federal Bailouts, 1913-1939.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=4E93474F-26EA-40DC-979F-D5978E92765B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Faffirmative-action-in-contracting-faces-legal-peril-balancing-economy-ag-sba-73911fdb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Wonder Land: Democrats said decades ago they alone would run policies for black Americans. Now comes the reckoning. Images: AP/Getty Images Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-in-contracting-faces-legal-peril-balancing-economy-ag-sba-73911fdb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-in-contracting-faces-legal-peril-balancing-economy-ag-sba-73911fdb<category> racial contracting</category><category> racial balancing</category><category> government contracting</category><category> race</category><category> fair admissions</category><category> affirmative action</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Contracts/Orders</category><category> Government Contracts/Orders</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Small/Medium Businesses</category><category> Workplace Discrimination/Abuse</category><category> Affirmative Action</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Society/Community</category><category> Crime/Legal Action</category><category>歧视</category><category>Ethnic Minorities</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>Politics/International Relations</category><category> Domestic Politics</category><category> Racism/Xenophobia</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Content Types</category><category> Commentaries/Opinions</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>contracts</category><category> orders</category><category> government contracts</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category>小的</category><category>medium businesses</category><category> workplace discrimination</category><category>虐待</category><category>political</category><category> general news</category><category> society</category><category> community</category><category> crime</category><category> legal action</category><category>歧视</category><category>ethnic minorities</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>politics</category><category> international relations</category><category> domestic politics</category><category> racism</category><category> xenophobia</category><category> social issues</category><category> content types</category><category> commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e executive news filter</category><category> c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category> opinion </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why SVB Financial Is Getting Off Easy in Bankruptcy Court]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Regulators didn&#39;t order the holding company to help. Now other banks are stuck with an unjust bill. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104881489493958"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104881489493958"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Todd H. Baker</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 6:22 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-svb-financial-is-getting-off-easy-in-bankruptcy-court-holding-company-strength-chapter-11-fdic-14ebcd2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823299?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Silicon Valley Bank&#39;s headquarters in Santa Clara, Calif., March 13.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Benjamin Fanjoy/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> What&#39;s the point of a bank holding company if it isn&#39;t a source of strength?</p><p> It&#39;s one thing to make the big banks foot the $16 billion bill for Silicon Valley Bank&#39;s risk-management failures, as the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is planning to do. It&#39;s another thing to ask them to pay those staggering sums when the unsecured creditors and shareholders of SVB Financial Group—the bank&#39;s holding company—walk away with billions that should have been used to help save the bank or reduce the FDIC&#39;s losses when it failed.</p><p> Yet such is the likely outcome of SVB&#39;s meltdown, which is being resolved in a Manhattan bankruptcy court. While we can expect a settlement in the dispute between the FDIC and the bankrupt holding company, the hedge-fund creditors and shareholders of SVB Financial are expected to come out of Chapter 11 reorganization with most of the organization&#39;s assets. That includes about $2 billion in cash, more than $9 billion in assets under management in its venture-capital subsidiary (as of December 2022), $100 million from the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/svb-securities-to-be-sold-for-100-million-a63aa112?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recent sale</a> of its investment-banking business, and a reported net operating loss carry-forward of nearly $11 billion.</p><p> Under federal law, a bank holding company is supposed to be a source of “financial strength” to its subsidiary bank. That means it must be equipped to help if the bank suffers “financial distress.” A holding company often has ample capacity to do so, especially if it owns other financial businesses.</p><p> SVB Financial was in the “very ample capacity” category, yet it provided no cash assistance to its subsidiary that was nearing collapse. Nothing in the public record suggests its regulators formally asked it to inject capital into the bank. Instead, the company held onto its reserves and launched an ill-advised effort to raise a similar amount in public markets, which served only to highlight impending distress and hasten the bank&#39;s demise.</p><p> How could this have happened? The answer lies in the long history of what is known as the “source of strength” doctrine. That doctrine has its founding in the Bank Holding Company Act of 1956, which required the Federal Reserve Board of Governors to take into consideration the financial and management resources of any company seeking approval to become a bank holding company. In <em>Board of Governors of FRS v. First Lincolnwood</em> (1978), the Supreme Court interpreted this provision to mean that the board could reject a holding company&#39;s application if it determined that the company “would not be a sufficient source of financial and managerial strength to its subsidiary Bank.”</p><p> In 1984 the Fed amended its “ <a href="https://thebhca.org/holding-companies-as-a-source-of-strength/#:~:text=The%20Federal%20Reserve%20amended%20its,policy%20statement%20making%20plain%20its" target="_blank" class="icon none">Regulation Y</a> ”—rules for bank holding companies—to state that a bank holding company must be a source of “financial and managerial strength” and “not conduct its operations in an unsafe or unsound manner.” The board added in a 1987 policy statement that holding companies “should stand ready to use available resources to provide adequate capital funds to its subsidiary banks during periods of financial stress” and that failure to do so would be deemed “unsafe and unsound.” While the Fed considered its policy binding, subsequent litigation muddied the waters without providing definitive guidance on any limits to the regulator&#39;s authority.</p><p> To what extent may the Fed order a holding company to transfer its funds to its troubled subsidiaries? Congress sought to answer that question in the Dodd-Frank Act of 2010, which stated that the overseeing federal regulatory agency “shall require the bank holding company . 。 。 to serve as a source of financial strength” for its subsidiaries. The law further clarified “source of financial strength” to mean the bank holding company&#39;s ability to “provide financial assistance” to its subsidiary “in the event of financial distress.”</p><p> In other words, Congress clarified the Fed&#39;s authority to make SVB Financial provide some of its abundant resources to its subsidiary to try to forestall its failure. It never did. What gives?</p><p> When President Obama signed Dodd-Frank on July 21, 2010, the law gave federal banking agencies one year to issue final rules on how they were to assess a holding company&#39;s “financial strength.” Yet for more than a decade the Fed, FDIC and Office of the Comptroller of the Currency ignored the deadline and neglected to propose or adopt specific regulations. Without clear guidelines, key questions about a holding company&#39;s obligations to its subsidiary and how to trigger them were left unresolved.</p><p> This ambiguity proved devastating. As we know from public testimony, the Fed failed to take enforcement action against SVB and SVB Financial under its already-established regulatory powers in the months before the failure. Even without new rules in place, it could have conceivably put SVB Financial under a cease-and-desist order for its risk-management and compliance failures and ordered it to inject needed cash into the bank. The holding company may have contested that order but instead was given as easy out by the Fed&#39;s inaction.</p><p> Bank regulators made another unforced error in their dealings with SVB Financial. The Bankruptcy Code requires a bankrupt bank holding company to assume any “commitment” with a federal regulator to maintain the capital of its subsidiary bank. The debtor holding company must immediately fill any capital deficit—or its case will be converted from Chapter 11 (reorganization) to Chapter 7 (liquidation), in which the regulator&#39;s claim for capital support will trump those of the holding company&#39;s creditors and shareholders.</p><p> But the Bankruptcy Code doesn&#39;t define what a “commitment” is, and courts have typically found that a written agreement or other formal enforcement action must exist prior to a bank&#39;s failure for any commitment to be recognized. Since regulators never imposed capital-focused enforcement on SVB or its holding company, it&#39;s unlikely any court will honor the FDIC&#39;s claims for reimbursement for unpaid capital support from SVB&#39;s Financial&#39;s receivership. That means that despite Congress&#39;s intent in Dodd-Frank to make source-of-strength obligations binding, the FDIC won&#39;t have a priority claim to the holding company&#39;s assets in bankruptcy.</p><p> The victims of these regulatory miscues are the countless shareholders and customers of banks that will make billions in unnecessary payments to replenish the FDIC&#39;s deposit-insurance fund. Thirteen years after Dodd-Frank, it&#39;s high time regulators adopted source-of-strength regulations—not at the snail&#39;s pace the Fed seems poised to walk, but pronto. Clarity now will prevent more avoidable catastrophes in the future.</p><p> <em>Mr. Baker is a senior fellow at Columbia University&#39;s Richman Center for Business, Law and Public Policy.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 22:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-svb-financial-is-getting-off-easy-in-bankruptcy-court-holding-company-strength-chapter-11-fdic-14ebcd2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-svb-financial-is-getting-off-easy-in-bankruptcy-court-holding-company-strength-chapter-11-fdic-14ebcd2<category> deposit insurance</category><category> fdic</category><category> fed</category><category> silicon valley bank</category><category> bankruptcy</category><category> source of strength</category><category> dodd-frank</category><category> manhattan</category><category> regulators</category><category>银行业</category><category>Commercial Banking</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Corporate Strategy/Planning</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Bankruptcy</category><category> Corporate Funding</category><category> Financing Agreements</category><category>企业行动</category><category>Corporate/Industrial News</category><category> Corporate Financial Difficulty</category><category> Corporate Organizational Restructuring</category><category> Economic News</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Crime/Legal Action</category><category> Politics/International Relations</category><category> Domestic Politics</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Commentaries/Opinions</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category> C&amp;E Industry News Filter</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Opinion</category><category> corporate strategy</category><category> planning</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>legal action</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>corporate funding</category><category> financing agreements</category><category>企业行动</category><category>corporate</category><category> industrial news</category><category> corporate financial difficulty</category><category> corporate organizational restructuring</category><category> economic news</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category> crime</category><category> politics</category><category> international relations</category><category> domestic politics</category><category> content types</category><category> commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e executive news filter</category><category> c&amp;e industry news filter</category><category> opinion</category><category> banking</category><category> commercial banking</category><category> credit</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘After the Bite’ Review: Sharks in the Water, Fear in Town]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Ivy Meeropol&#39;s documentary on HBO investigates a deadly Cape Cod shark attack&#39;s profound effects on the surrounding community and the ethical dilemmas that arose. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108161897505390"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822606?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A shark in &#39;After the Bite&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: HBO </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108161897505390"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">John Anderson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 5:41 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-the-bite-review-sharks-in-the-water-fear-in-town-9e18016"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> From the beaches to the boat slips to the open Atlantic, the Cape Cod captured by director Ivy Meeropol&#39;s “After the Bite” looks like the most beautiful place on Earth. Paradise. And as befits such an image, there&#39;s a serpent in the garden. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>After the Bite</strong></p><p> <em>Wednesday, 10 pm, HBO</em></p></div></div><p> A fish, actually: the great white shark, which over the past decade or so has become an increasingly common and wholly unwelcome inhabitant of the waters off eastern-most Massachusetts. The ostensible focus of Ms. Meeropol&#39;s marvelously photographed and marvelously balanced documentary, the great white is drawn to the Cape by an exploding seal population, but the apex predator will eat what it can catch: In September 2018, a young man named Arthur Medici died as the result of a shark assault off Newcomb Hollow Beach in the town of Wellfleet. That incident followed by only a month what had been the first shark attack on the Cape in six years.</p><p> No casualties have occurred in the area since, we are told in a postscript, but that is likely a result of increased awareness, and that awareness is no small thing, not among the people who live and work full-time on the Cape or the hordes who visit in summer (prime time for sharks). With awareness come changes; as the film&#39;s title asserts, life has not been the same on the outer Cape since the Medici death. “Did we just get punched in the face?” asks local Dana Franchitto, remembering the community&#39;s reaction at the time. “That&#39;s what it felt like.”</p><p> Ms. Meeropol is the rare social-issue documentarian who isn&#39;t also a propagandist. In her 2015 film, “Indian Point,” she devoted as much time and space to the people who were keeping the Westchester County nuclear plant safe and running as she did to the forces trying to shut it down. There is no pro-shark-bite lobby in “After the Bite,” and the theory that warming waters are driving species north is more or less a given. But there are clashes of philosophy and practical action that need sorting out, and “After the Bite” treats both sides with respect.</p><p> The differences are mostly between defenders of the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, which was intended to help the then-endangered gray seal survive, and those who believe the species has survived sufficiently—and who believe that humans should, perhaps, be considered part of the ecosystem that such legislation is meant to sustain. As we learn in the film, as many as 20,000 seals were “bountied” or killed during the first half of the 20th century, their noses or ears cut off and redeemed for cash; they were believed to be a danger to the Cape Cod fishery and the people whose livelihoods depended on it. Now, the gray seals, with no predator but the shark, have grown to the point that they occupy certain beaches like pigeons in a New York City park.</p><p> The Marine Mammal Protection Act, meanwhile, appears unassailable, which bewilders locals. “Why should the seals have [priority] over people?” asks Crocker Snow, an owner of Muskeget Island, 20 miles south of the Cape and the principal gray seal breeding ground; approximately 3,000 pups were born there in one year. “To me, that&#39;s a big argument.”</p><p> The very existence of the Atlantic White Shark Conservancy seems to rankle some of the locals. “The number one role of government is public safety,” Wellfleet resident John Kartsounis tells a town council meeting. “Not shark safety. Not shark conservation.” Mr. Kartsounis is part of the Committee to Amend the Marine Mammal Protection Act, which makes its case. But as we see, most of the very immediate measures for safety are being executed by the Conservancy, which tags the sharks, floats electronic receivers on buoys and maintains an app called Sharktivity, by which bathers can follow shark movement through beach areas. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Television Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-heiress-and-the-heist-review-from-debutante-to-militant-2fecf1f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Heiress and the Heist&#39; Review: From Debutante to Militant</a> <span class="date">July 25, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/son-of-a-critch-review-a-comics-chaotic-coming-of-age-abb4ea14?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Son of a Critch&#39; Review: A Comic&#39;s Chaotic Coming-of-Age</a> <span class="date">July 20, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stephen-curry-underrated-review-a-warriors-mettle-ce20721e?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Stephen Curry: Underrated&#39; Review: A Warrior&#39;s Mettle</a> <span class="date">July 20, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/black-sands-review-perilous-prospects-nordic-noir-b39e9aa8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Black Sands&#39; Review: Perilous Prospects, Nordic Noir</a> <span class="date">July 18, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> There&#39;s quite a bit of what might be called shark-ology in “After the Bite,” and a variety of perspectives. Writer Alec Wilkinson, who knows the Cape well and remembers when a glimpse of a seal was an event, says the presence of sharks in the waters so close by puts one in touch with “power, violence; the truly unsympathetic quality of life.” Provincetown lobster fisherman Paul Tasha is just one of the many in the film to make a “Jaws” reference, while recalling an enormous shark he saw on a day the water was particularly clear (“which makes me wonder how many I didn&#39;t see when it was murky”). Mitzi Riley, who was there the day the 26-year-old Medici was killed, recalls mournfully that “there was no helping this poor boy,” his wounds being so severe and the action so sudden. “I had no idea what the hell just happened.”</p><p> One gets an idea when a crew from the Center for Coastal Studies visits the corpse of a humpback whale that has died and is being reabsorbed into the system—petrels flock around the bloated body, which will eventually sink and become an underwater buffet. And then the sharks come, one monstrous specimen rising out of the deep as if materializing out of a nightmare. The bite that he puts on the whale is awesome, unnerving and certainly humbling for those eager to go boogie-boarding. At the same time, this particular lunch is keeping one hungry fish off the beach.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Anderson is the Journal&#39;s TV critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 21:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-the-bite-review-sharks-in-the-water-fear-in-town-9e18016</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-the-bite-review-sharks-in-the-water-fear-in-town-9e18016<category> arts in review</category><category> Animal Attacks</category><category> Animal Rights</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> Society/Community</category><category> Crime/Legal Action</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category>自然环境</category><category>电影</category><category>Environmental Protection</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Television/Radio</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> animal attacks</category><category> animal rights</category><category> political</category><category> general news</category><category> society</category><category> community</category><category> crime</category><category> legal action</category><category> arts</category><category> entertainment</category><category>自然环境</category><category>movies</category><category> environmental protection</category><category> social issues</category><category> television</category><category> radio</category><category> content types</category><category> factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category> reviews </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Henry V’ and ‘Love’s Labor’s Lost’ Reviews: Shakespeare in a Sandbox]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In its new location, the long-established Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival brings a youthful verve and overlapping cast to the playwright&#39;s popular war story and introspective romantic comedy. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108103476094736"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822683?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sean McNall, Luis Quintero, Francis Pàce-Nuñez and Carl Howell in &#39;Henry V&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: T Charles Erickson </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108103476094736"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Charles Isherwood</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 25, 2023 5:37 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/henry-v-and-loves-labors-lost-reviews-shakespeare-in-a-sandbox-418c013e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Garrison, NY</em></p><p> It has become rare to see two Shakespeare plays running in repertory with overlapping casts. This alone makes a pilgrimage to the Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival a rewarding endeavor—the theatrical equivalent of a trek to a zoo or a botanical garden to check out the exotic species on view.</p><p> What&#39;s more, the plays programmed by artistic director Davis McCallum are smartly contrasted: <strong>“Henry V”</strong> is Shakespeare&#39;s most popular and accessible history play, while the rarely produced “Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost” represents his comedy at its most esoteric, despite the farcical machinations of its plot. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Henry V</strong></p><p> <strong>Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost</strong></p><p> <em>Hudson Valley Shakespeare Festival, 2015 Route 9, Garrison, NY, $10-$100, 845-265-9575, “Henry V” closes Aug. 21, “Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost” closes Aug. 27</em></p></div></div><p> The company, founded in 1987, is in transition, having moved last year to a new campus, a former golf course that is being landscaped to make audiences less likely to imagine a shanked ball knocking them unconscious. A new amphitheater is under construction, but the current, tented space is pleasingly intimate. The stage is simply a square expanse of sand, and I couldn&#39;t shake the happy notion that watching the mostly young cast performing the plays with infectious exuberance was akin to observing precociously clever kids playing in a sandbox.</p><p> “Henry V,” with its mighty conflict between England and France and rah-rah fervor, lends itself to pomp and pageantry. (It has been lavishly filmed twice, by Laurence Olivier and Kenneth Branagh. ) But this stripped-bare production, directed by Mr. McCallum, is closer to what audiences might have seen in Shakespeare&#39;s day; the prologue acknowledges the impossibility of representing the momentous events depicted and calls on the audience to “let us . 。 。 on your imaginary forces work” and to “piece out our imperfections with your thoughts.”</p><p> One is easily persuaded to obey the invitation since Sean McNall, who plays the chorus, offering further elucidation of the action throughout, is superb. He delivers his speeches with conversational ease while displaying a tight grasp of Shakespearean style and rhythm.</p><p> The contemporary production is marked by many other fine turns. The comic subplot featuring the squabbles among the lowly characters— Francis Pàce-Nuñez&#39;s Bardolph, Luis Quintero&#39;s Pistol and Carl Howell&#39;s Nym—are robustly funny. Duane Boutté also stands out in two contrasting roles, the scheming Archbishop of Canterbury and the noble King of France.</p><p> The one disappointing performance, unhappily, was Emily Ota&#39;s in the title role. Swaggering in a red-and-white motorcycle jacket, she presents a commanding figure. But when delivering Henry&#39;s exhortations to his troops, including the well-known set pieces, before Harfleur (“Once more unto the breach . . .”) and the St. Crispin&#39;s Day speech (“We few, we happy few . . .”), Ms. Ota sometimes resorts to shouty bluster and a surface bravado that falls short of bringing the language to poetic life. Fortunately “Henry V” is so rich in incident that even a less than fully satisfying turn in the title role cannot dampen its durable dramatic appeal.</p><h4> ***</h4><p> <strong>“Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost”</strong> is also presented in contemporary costuming, and director Amanda Dehnert&#39;s freewheeling production aims to bridge the distance between the play&#39;s coruscating, at times devilishly hard-to-parse language and the sensibilities of today&#39;s audiences. Ms. Dehnert has brought out the scissors, vigorously trimming Shakespeare&#39;s words, in part to make room for original songs she composed with André Pluess. While some might frown at this as desecration, it struck me as an inventive way of translating Shakespeare&#39;s depiction of the follies of youth and romantic infatuation into the zeitgeist of Gen Z, or whatever Gen we are currently dissecting. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822690?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Antoinette Robinson, Phoebe Lloyd, Mayadevi Ross and Emily Ota in &#39;Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: T Charles Erickson</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The deliciously devised plot ignites when the King of Navarre (a stately Omar Shafiuzzaman ) invites three of his lords to join him in forswearing all diversions—mainly women—for three years, devoting themselves only to study. The plan, initially agreed to with varying degrees of reluctance by Berowne (the insouciant Stephen Michael Spencer ), Longaville (Mr. Pàce-Nuñez) and Dumain (Lennon Xin Wen Hu), quickly goes spectacularly awry. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Theater Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/here-lies-love-review-david-byrnes-dictator-disco-party-a84cc46d?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Here Lies Love&#39; Review: David Byrne&#39;s Dictator Disco Party</a> <span class="date">July 20, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-saviour-review-irish-repertory-marie-mullen-c110ed97?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Saviour&#39; Review: Doubt Intrudes on Delight</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-whos-tommy-and-another-marriage-reviews-pinball-wizards-coupled-writers-1912765e?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Who&#39;s Tommy&#39; and &#39;Another Marriage&#39; Reviews: Pinball Wizards, Coupled Writers</a> <span class="date">July 6, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hamlet-review-shakespeare-in-the-park-with-a-modern-twist-15c9229e?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Hamlet&#39; Review: Shakespeare in the Park With a Modern Twist</a> <span class="date">June 29, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> No sooner have the lords committed themselves than there arrives an embassy from France, led by the Princess ( Phoebe Lloyd, regal but approachable) and—wouldn&#39;t you know?—three of her ladies, Rosaline (a stately, sharp-tongued Antoinette Robinson</p> ), Maria (Ms. Ota, radiant and unrecognizable as the same actor who played Henry) and Katharine (Mayadevi Ross). The men&#39;s vows are tossed in a paper-shredder as they tumble into besotted adoration of the comely ladies.<p></p><p> The convolutions of Shakespeare&#39;s scenario are too detailed to delineate. A major subplot, wonderfully unfolded here, involves the rivalry between Sir Adrian O. Dearmaddow (an anglicized version of Don Adriano de Armado), played with pompous good humor by Kurt Rhoads, and the “clown” Costard, portrayed with cheeky appeal (and a red rubber nose) by Mr. Quintero, over the affections of Jaquenetta, imbued with a wised-up attitude by Melissa Mahoney. Timothy Bright brings a tartly witty buoyancy to his role as Sir Adrian&#39;s page and comic foil.</p><p> Unlike most of the comedies, “Love&#39;s Labor&#39;s Lost” concludes on a note of melancholy, as the Princess receives news that her father has died. This puts to an end the barbed and witty exchanges between the lovers. “Youth isn&#39;t wasted on the young,” sings Jaquenetta in the opening song. But the play&#39;s ending acknowledges that youth, with its innocence and headlong emotional abandon, must evolve into maturity, and the attendant ambiguous wisdom it brings. This playful production does not attempt to gloss over the shadows encroaching, but leaves its characters in an uneasy limbo between heedlessness and responsibility.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Isherwood is the Journal&#39;s theater critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 21:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/henry-v-and-loves-labors-lost-reviews-shakespeare-in-a-sandbox-418c013e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/henry-v-and-loves-labors-lost-reviews-shakespeare-in-a-sandbox-418c013e<category> arts in review</category><category> Political/General News</category><category> National/Public Security</category><category> Arts/Entertainment</category><category> Festivals</category><category> Risk News</category><category> Theater</category><category> Military Action</category><category> Content Types</category><category> Factiva Filters</category><category> C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>评论</category><category>Arts in Review</category><category> SYND</category><category> WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> political</category><category> general news</